    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>Judson treats rings in Ch. 16 and ideals in Ch. 16-17. We compress this because the definition is straightforward: a ring is an abelian group with a second associative operation that distributes. The integers are the motivating example. Commutative rings with identity (the common case in algebra) are assumed throughout. The connection to Milewski's sum/product types is informal: types under (+, *) satisfy distributivity but lack additive inverses, making them a semiring rather than a ring.</p>

